Hi Claire, and BonAppetit as a whole, I have no idea how "submissions" are even considered, but I have three that I think are perfect considerations, especially for the coming Summer HEAT: 1. Chipwich - What I love and miss about this once widely accessible American treat was the soft cookies that the ice cream sat between, particularly because it was something between a baked chocolate chip cookie and a disk of chocolate chip cookie dough. Cooked, but with that perfect, creamy texture. Not sure how that is even possible. The vanilla ice cream was basic and could be improved upon, but the true icing on the cake were the dark chocolate mini chocolate chips that coated the outer edge of the ice cream. A true camptime favorite! 2. ChocoTaco - This is another camp favorite and the biggest challenge choices. The dark chocolate dipped waffel cone taco--amazing! The layers of chocolate leaves between ice cream on the interior for that extra crunch--genius! The chopped nut sprinkle--complete! 3. Sour Candy - This is more an overarching category that includes many options, and it is something you still haven''t done! As someone who has to import American sour favorites, I have tried to make my own sour candies without the help of highly processed syrups (attempting all natural/organic, vegan, and low sugar options, and it is so nuanced that I think it would be a great challenge! Finding the proper balances between fruit, citrus and various food acid types is a brilliant and vibrant journey! Particular inspirations would be Sour Patch Kids, Sour Patch Watermelons, Warheads (the hard candy version with a sour burst also in the middle), Sour Cherries, original Sour Skittles, Sour Punch straws and strips, and two European favorites of mine (the only things sour enough for me in Europe): the German version of Sour Happy Cola gummies by Haribo, and a new candy in the Netherlands called Zure Matjes by a brand called Katja.

I made something Nutella-y last Christmas - I basically made hazelnut butter in my blender then kept adding cocoa powder, salt and icing sugar until I got the colour and flavour I wanted. Nowhere near the texture of the actual stuff - it was bitty and much more like rough peanut butter - and it was too dark cocoa-wise for my housemate, but it tasted amazing and is definitely something I would be making with my kid when she's old enough; Nutella is, yeah, pretty much just chocolate icing, despite it being yummy, and I found making a chocolatey hazelnut butter essentially was much nicer. Video was too long. Halfway through it, I got hungry so I left it playing and went to the kitchen to fix my self a sandwich. But then I found out that I'm out of mayonnaise so I went to a store. There, I saw the most beautiful woman I have ever seen in my whole life. But I'm really a shy person so I took up a three-year personality development course so I can introduce my self. She was very friendly and all, but unfortunately, she has a boyfriend. So I said, all good, I'm a mature person. I want the best for her and I harbor no illusion that I am the best person for her and she seems happy with her boyfriend, so I did not bother her anymore. But we kept in touch and we became friends and I got over my crush on her. Then she broke up with her boyfriend, we drank some alcohol because of it, I told her she'll be fine and I wished her well. I still think she's the most beautiful woman in the world, but like I said, I am over my crush on her. It was like five years already when I first saw her. Besides, I am quiet happy with the friendship I developed with her. It was more important than a crush. So we kept hanging out, drinking, having coffee, and all. I had a girlfriend, she started dating other guys. My girlfriend wants to live some other life without me in it, so I said, okay, I want the best for you and I want you to pursue your happiness. My lady friend and I drank alcohol about it, and she gave me the same advice I gave her when she was in that position and I became okay with the breakup immediately. But we were really drunk, so she spent the night in my apartment. I only have one bed, so you know what that means: She took the bed and I slept on the couch. But on the couch, I really can't sleep. Something was bothering me. So I tossed and turned for about three hours, then I finally can't take it anymore, I stood up and went straight to my room where she's sleeping. I approached the bed, gently sat on it and I reached for her shoulder to pull her closer to me. She stirred and woke up. She asked what's up. I told her, you know, the first time I saw you, I was watching a video and left it playing to get my self a sandwich then went to the store to get some mayo then I got distracted by life that I forgot to finish the video. She said, you know what, I've been wondering about a weird noise in your night drawer. So we opened that drawer, and lo and behold, there's my phone and this video still has two minutes of play time on it.

MADOGA writes...  what would motivate an employer to give someone a job with way out of date experience and an old degree ?  What would motivate ANYBODY to give ANYBODY a job by your reasoning? It is always tough starting out in a profession or re-entering the workforce after some time off. While difficult, eventually somebody offers most of us a job, we gain experience and after 6 months this myth about us not being able to perform due to having no experience is dispelled. OP's wife WILL get a job eventually if she keeps trying, mark my word...  Also to be fair the skill of coding hasn't changed much since 2011. Neither have network protocols...etc.  My concern is that the SE Asian degree and overseas experience will mean zero so she's starting from square 1 (and clearly 'best uni in SE Asia' is at very best a contentious claim unless it's the National University of Singapore which is ranked higher than most GO8 unis...so don't make that claim if it's some random joint in the Philippines or whatever because it's a lie).  Call me rude/cynical but when I worked in job services EVERYBODY from SE Asia was like 'oh yeah I'm an engineer/doctor/accountant/teacher...etc in my home country... best uni, very high class... but your country doesn't recognise this!!!' I'd then break down their skills and EVERY TIME I would be like 'you little liar!!! We call that skill book keeping not accounting...etc no I can't help you get a $100k a year job with an accounting firm...'  What I'd put to here is... does she legitimately have the skills required? What can she build? Give her a computer... can she make an iPhone app or something, for example? If so, why can't she setup a business and build a portfolio?  Story: my father in law is an 'architect' in SE Asia. Conversation... 'oh yeah, what kinda houses do you design?' will get the answer 'hahaha I work for the government boy... highly respected architect!!' Pretty quickly you realise that he's got some kinda TAFE qual (at best) and he's an admin clerk for the government's town planning authority, who takes bribes to approve stuff... hence why an otherwise dull job is a plumb gig in SE Asia. He makes enough money to be treated like a king over there and I have no reason to challenge him as he's family. However, his definition of 'architect' and mine are vastly different. Lesson: SE Asia is the wild west and everybody exaggerates their importance/education so such things should be taken with a grain of salt. Â @kenzaghodbane5890Â

@@Home Love The appropriateness of giving a host something has very little to do with it being cheap or not. Ferrero Rocher is a finished product, delicious, attractively packaged, and as far as gifts go, pretty cheap. I love them, and would much appreciate them as a gift. Nutella itself would be an odd gift, unless it came as part of a gift basket, then it would be lovely. Most ingredients in candy and desserts are cheap, starting with sugar. And no, I would not expect a Michelin star restaurant to serve McDonald's french fries. Possibly their own french fries, which are made with, surprise, the fact same ingredients as McDonald's fries. Nor would I compare an an appropriate everyday hostess gift with a Michelin star restaurant. If, as a guest, my ambition was to be 'classy' on a Michelin star level, I absolutely do not think a box of Ferrero Rocher would suffice. Something like Godiva would be more appropriate for such an occasion.

I very purposefully wrote supermarket CHECKOUT LINES in the post you are replying to. Sorry about the all caps, not intending to yell, just emphasizing that I was specifically referring to that location within the store. This might sound ridiculous but I am so glad that this was the first video that appeared on my homepage when I opened YouTube this evening. I don't usually leave comments on videos nor have I ever been this open on a public forum but I felt I had to. I had been really struggling with my depression the last few weeks. In fact right before this I was searching for something to cut myself with but since I couldn't find anything I thought it better to just find a distraction to keep my mind off how bad I felt. Claire's videos on BA are my favourite thing and I've scoured the Internet to make sure I've seen every single one because she is just my absolute fave. There is something I find weirdly calming about her videos and this one in particular saved me from doing something stupid like relapsing back into self harm after having been clean for a year after suffering for almost 10 years.  So this is just a silly comment to say thank you so much for continuing to make videos with BA and BA for just being an overall fun and amazing channel. You guys really helped me out tonight even if you were just doing your jobs.

For instance, German Nutella is much thicker than French Nutella. One reason for that is probably that German (half-)rye bread is a lot sturdier than French white bread. The latter would tear up with the German version as a spread, while the rye bread holds form. Things like that are true all over the place. Eastern European Nutella is (or at least used to be) made with more palm oil and fewer hazelnuts and less chocolate than the German version. This might be for cost/price reasons, or for similar preference reasons. So it's very much possible that the Australian version has thicker filling than the US version, since its Nutella might be different.

Especially with the episode before this one, it seemed to be all about recreating the thing as closely as possible instead of making an actual gourmet version.  Here, for example, I would've loved to see a better cream on the inside. Why not a dark chocolate-coffee mousse? And a more interesting nut than hazelnut, let's say macadamia. Or maybe make a pistachio version. Why not different versions, see what's the best? There could've been so much improvement on the chocolate itself, too, and the wafers. Something akin to stroopwafels maybe? To me, a gourmet version of a Rocher would be something that looks like a Rocher, has the same basic building blocks (nut inside, covered in filling, enveloped by a spherical wafer, covered in more nut brittle, covered in chocolate) but uses far better ingredients and variations of the original.  I'm not hating on Claire or the show, just trying to offer some constructive criticism. Like I said, I do love the show and I do enjoy it a whole lot. I'd just enjoy it even more if an actual gourmet version would be attempted.

When she had the oil of her "nutella" attempt separated from the solids I really understood her struggle.  Short story time: When I was a baker in france, we used to do lots of marzipan for the holidays, which is basically almond powder with syrup and then kneaded. If you were not careful enough and the dough got too warm by an excess of kneading, the almond oil will separate 10 out of 10 times, and when the oil starts to come out, YOU'RE SCREWED, there's no way to put that mofo back in again. So you're basically stuck having a pool of oil and some chunks of sweet, sticky almond paste.  Claire, I feel you sis. I really do.

If only Claire had a food scientist to consult with on these projects.  I know that people like to bash on "dirty ingredient lines" but there is a specific reason for each and every ingredient in packaged products like ferrero rochers.  The filling kept breaking because of the interaction of oils and water in the ingredients. Lecithin is an emulsifier used to prevent that.  And palm oil is used for its specific melting point and overall fatty acid profile which is what gives nutella the texture it has.  When you make fundamental changes to the chemistry of the product, it greatly changes the flavor delivery, texture, stability, everything.

JohnMJ writes...  lineman is what I really want to do  Hey mate I'm a qualified electrical fitter mechanic (electrician) that did my apprenticeship at and still work for a supply authority. I think you'll find it is competitive to be a linesman but not as competitive as say an electrician position is. My biggest regret when completing my application was for not selecting linesman as my preferred trade. My company hires linesman, communication technicians, electricians and cablejointers. However during my intake they were only looking for electricians or linesman. Being young and dumb I didn't know what a linesman was so chose electrician.  I had to do two maths tests, general aptitude, mechanical aptitude, literacy and a personality test. Then a panel interview and a fit for work appointment and drug test.  I was fortunate in my company as unlike lots of supply authorities the electricians aren't confined to zone substation work. In my time I did lots of linesman work such as stringing overhead services, running bundled conductors and streetlights. Also did a lots of cablejointer work such as terminating HV cables into switchgear, HV cable pulls down streets and HV cablejoints. Even HV cable terminations on top of powerpoles. As an electrician I was also allowed to do lots of LV switching work, LV cable joins, transformer work, no power complaints and was lucky in that aspect because lots of callouts and overtime.  Overall the electrician is a better trade but from my work experience at the company I'm more comfortable doing cablejointing and linesman work then say control wiring or house wiring. I've also seen lots of cablejointers and linesman dual trade to electricians but its a lot harder for an electrician to dual trade the other way. Also lots of work for linesman and cablejointers out there and usually good money working for supply authorities.  money_killer writes... All sheep are killed once their hair yield drops below a certain point, mostly around 4 years old. They could live to be 12.
